##Four strikes of new crown disease, globalization is going backwards?

I-CAIJING

CAIJING magazine official Wechat. "CAIJING" magazine, sponsored by the China Securities Market Research Center, was first published in 1998, adhering to the news concept of "independence, exclusiveness and originality" , and is known for authoritative, impartial and professional reporting, it is a must-read publication for policy-makers, researchers and managers in the field of politics and economics.

The further spread of the global epidemic will have a greater impact on the global economy, and the prospects for global cooperation are not optimistic because the international situation is already very different from that at the onset of the global financial crisis, a fourth shock wave to the global economy could follow

Wen | he fan, Zhu he, Xu Peiyu, Huang Wanjing

The new coronavirus has spread around the world, with the World Health Organization describing it as a "pandemic" . Although several of the more severely affected countries have begun to adopt more robust prevention and control measures, including restrictions on the movement of people, the closure of businesses, and home-based work by employees, most countries are still in the early stages of prevention and control, measures are not yet in place. This is bound to affect the further spread of the global epidemic, will also bring a greater impact on the global economy.

At present, the impact of the new crown epidemic on the global economy has three main aspects: supply shocks, demand shocks and balance sheet losses. It remains to be seen whether the outbreak will lead to a global economic crisis. But the worry is that with the international situation already very different from what it was at the time of the global financial crisis, the prospects for global cooperation are not promising, and the outbreak of the new crown is likely to bring with it a fourth shock wave to the global economy: The receding tide of globalization. In the face of the impact of the new crown disease, China should be vigilant, prepared, sufficient policy space, or can reduce the negative impact of the epidemic on China's economy.

The first shock: supply shocks from global supply chains

###The first shock: supply shocks from global supply chains

China was the first country to experience a new outbreak of the disease, which affected production in various industries for a time. Given that China is already the world's second-largest economy, and in particular its economy is more integrated into global supply chains, this would have a larger supply shock to the global economy.

How do you measure the supply shock to global supply chains? One direct approach is to use the international input-output table database to measure China's impact on the global economy. On the face of it, this method is the most direct and systematic one, which should lead to a clear and reliable conclusion, but in reality, it may encounter various difficulties. First, the input output table is not the actual statistical data, the process of calculation needs to be based on the bottom of the Input-output model to make a lot of estimates and projections, in this process there will be a lot of estimation bias. Cross-country input-output table will be faced with this problem, the statistical standards of different countries will further magnify the error of the input-output table. The second is that the input output table is a linear mechanism found through a group of simultaneous equations, while the actual economic mechanism is mostly nonlinear and has a lot of positive and negative feedback effects. Third, the key to estimate the impact level is to determine the magnitude of the original impact, but the information of the original impact assessment is seriously inadequate. In other words, if we can't measure the magnitude of the impact on China with relative accuracy, we can't estimate the impact on the global economy, and we have to use different scenarios. In fact, that's why most of the models we're seeing measuring the impact of the epidemic on the global economy are based on scenario analysis.

We are trying to measure more directly the supply impact of the new crown disease on the global supply chain from another angle. The idea is to use raw, real world trade data to identify countries that are more vulnerable to China's shocks. These countries import more Chinese products, especially intermediate products. Imports of intermediate goods are intended to enter the domestic production chain and clearly have a more direct impact on the country's production. By identifying these more vulnerable countries, we can judge the supply impact of the new crown disease on global supply chains by their distribution and size.

We calculated the share of the world's imports of intermediate goods in total imports, the share of China's imports of intermediate goods in total imports of intermediate goods, and the share of the world's total trade in GDP. If a country's first two indicators are relatively high, then that country is highly dependent on China's imports of intermediate goods. On this basis, if the country also has a high degree of dependence on foreign trade, then the country's overall economy is more dependent on China's imports, which indicates that the country will be more affected by the new crown epidemic.

As the chart shows, the countries that are more dependent on international trade, have stronger links to international supply chains and import more intermediate goods from China are mostly developing countries with few developed economies. Of course, in some industries, some developed countries and China have very close links in the production and consumption links. For example, in the electronics industry, China, Japan and South Korea formed the East Asian production system with China as the core, in the automobile industry, Germany is highly dependent on China's terminal demand.

How long will this supply shock last? Although the current Chinese enterprises have not yet fully resumed production, but from the current progress, Chinese enterprises back to normal production only a matter of time. Supply shocks come first, but they also subside first. At the same time, it is worth pointing out that the current global supply chain is still a division of labor around developed economies, and China's unique position in the global supply chain is irreplaceable by other emerging economies, therefore, as long as there is no systemic crisis in global supply chains, there is no reason to believe that such supply shocks will have a lasting impact.

However, as Chinese companies gradually return to normal production, new problems will surface. Do you still have all the export orders that we thought we were gonNA have to work overtime?

Second Shock: Shrinking aggregate demand due to epidemic prevention and control

###Second Shock: Shrinking aggregate demand due to epidemic prevention and control

The current global market concern is no longer whether China can resume work, but the impact of new crown disease on aggregate demand. As the epidemic spread around the world, governments were forced to take all kinds of preventive measures, which also raised concerns in the financial markets. A number of stock markets around the world have plummeted. Even the IMF, which has a habit of overestimating global growth, says the global economy will be worse in 2020 than it was in 2019.

At present, it is difficult to judge the impact of aggregate demand, and the market expectation is confused. The main reason is that the concept of epidemic prevention and anti-epidemic in different countries in the world is very different, and the measures taken are still changing. Different epidemic prevention and anti-epidemic measures will bring different impact on demand.

If, according to the degree of Rigor, a spectrum of national responses to the epidemic is made, then China is at one end of the spectrum and the United States'initial response is at the other. Because of the experience of the SARS epidemic in 2003, China has taken severe measures from the very beginning, including closing cities and stopping production and classes. This mode of fighting the epidemic can better control the epidemic situation, but due to the suppression of consumption and the restriction of the movement of people, the disruption to demand is also greater. South Korea's approach is similar to China's, and the effect is broadly similar. On the other hand, a more laissez faire approach would appear to be less disruptive to the economy, but the epidemic would spread more rapidly and require more remedial action later, as is currently the case in Italy and Iran.

Many countries were initially closer to the US than to China, but the trend is for more and more governments to change their positions and move in China's direction, with even the US government taking tougher action. This means that the next epidemic prevention and anti-epidemic measures on the overall demand suppression effect will be stronger and stronger. The developed world is largely tertiary sector of the economy, with consumption accounting for a higher share of GDP, so restricting the movement of people and closing public areas would have a greater impact on their economies. For Emerging Economies, falling demand in the developed world means falling external demand, which naturally adds to domestic economic pressures.

With the development of the epidemic, one factor that has a greater impact on demand is the ability of countries to prevent and Control Infectious Diseases. Developed countries have established a relatively perfect public health care system, with a strong primary health care capacity, and the resilience and efficiency of their health care system is significantly higher than that of developing countries. Once these countries begin to realize the seriousness of the epidemic, and to activate the prevention and control system of infectious diseases, control of the new crown epidemic is not a difficult thing. Moreover, these areas have not yet seen a concentrated outbreak, which is less stressful than the treatment that China faced in the early stages of the epidemic.

It is developing countries with relatively poor health conditions that are really at risk of major problems. We use the World Health Organization's Universal Health Coverage Index (UHC) to measure countries'primary care capacity. The construction of the index involves many aspects, and is limited by the availability and authenticity of relevant data in some countries, and can not directly compare the level of medical care in different countries. However, the index is better suited to measure primary health care in developing countries, especially less developed countries, than in developed economies. We combined the UHC index with the trade status of each country to assess their exposure to the epidemic.

According to the World Health Organization, China's UHC is about 79. If this is used as a cutoff point for defining prevention and control capabilities, then all countries with a UHC value of no more than 79, with the exception of China, together account for about 30 per cent of global trade, these countries account for about 35% of China's total exports. In other words, about a third of China's external demand may not be able to respond adequately to the outbreak. Any problems in these countries could further weaken China's external demand.

The third shock: The short-term deterioration of the balance sheet

###The third shock: The short-term deterioration of the balance sheet

In addition to a supply and demand shock, the impact of new crown disease on the balance sheet is relatively hidden. New Crown Disease can directly affect the balance sheet of all sectors of society through two mechanisms. First, prevention and control of the epidemic will bring a certain degree of economic stagnation, the departments in the short term will therefore bear the corresponding loss of liquidity, which will be directly reflected in the asset-side of the additional consumption of current assets. Second, the financial market in panic selling behavior, and lead to a rapid decline in asset prices, which will make the corresponding departments of financial assets value, reduce the value of assets.

Under the first mechanism, each department bears the loss of liquidity rather than the actual loss. This gap could be gradually filled later with additional liquidity. This is clear in China. In order to prevent and control the epidemic, the production, circulation and consumption of the Chinese economy have temporarily come to a halt. During this period, most economic agents did not create any economic value, or GDP. Using the production method, we estimate that about 25-30 days will be lost during the period from February to April due to complete shutdown and loss of efficiency, totaling 8 trillion yuan.

Among them, some of the industrial companies in the upper and middle reaches, which make up about 30 percent of the secondary sector of the economy, have been less affected. Some services, such as finance and online consumption, are unaffected, accounting for about 50% of tertiary sector of the economy. Combine that with the secondary sector of the economy and tertiary sector of the economy share of GDP, and you end up with a liquidity gap of 4 to 5 trillion yuan. These are not actual profit losses, but cash flow losses. Some firms are actually using their cash flow to supplement cash flows from other sectors, or to compensate for changes in their balance sheets, says cash flow statement, an economist at UBS.

The government's tax and other revenues will fall and banks will suffer some interest losses as a result of the outbreak, but it is the corporate and residential sectors that will bear the bulk of the liquidity gap. For the household sector, it is impossible to increase debt to make up for the cash flow gap, only consumption savings. The corporate sector can consume current liquidity or obtain short-term loans from the financial sector. Either way, leverage in both sectors will be forced up in the short term.

Based on the 2019 data, the monthly net cash flow of residents and enterprises is estimated to increase by 500-600 billion yuan, which means that it will take at least 6-8 months for residents and enterprises to complete the repair of their balance sheets, that is, until the third quarter of 2020. In this period, the resident's durable goods consumption and the enterprise's fixed assets investment will be directly affected.

For advanced economies, the collapse in asset values resulting from the recent sharp correction in financial markets will have a direct impact on the balance sheets of various sectors. America's 401K plan links household sector pensions directly to financial markets, where a slump could shrink the size of household sector pension accounts, affecting current and future consumer spending. This would have a direct impact on the US economy. The magnitude of this impact is not easy to estimate at the moment, as things are still evolving, but as long as financial markets do not return to calm and past levels in a short period of time, the balance sheets of the entity sector will suffer, it's GonNa take time to fix.

The balance-sheet losses of any mechanism ultimately point to the fact that, having lost the spending power of both the household and the corporate sectors, the only force that can fill the demand gap and stabilize aggregate demand is the government sector. In terms of the economic cycle, the new crown epidemic interrupted the weak global economic recovery that emerged at the end of 2019. If the government can't fill that gap and get the economy moving again, that means the economy will have to stay at the bottom longer. This is going to be the hardest part of the real economy.

Fourth Shock: The EBB tide of globalization

###Fourth Shock: The EBB tide of globalization

The epidemic of new crown is a common problem in all countries of the world. On March 12,2020, the G20's second meeting of G20 facilitators issued the G20 facilitators'statement on new crown pneumonia, agreeing to use all available policy tools, including appropriate fiscal and monetary measures, to meet the challenge of the new crown disease. While this sends a positive signal, global economic cooperation is already in a very different position than it was a decade ago when the global financial crisis erupted, and the new crown epidemic may not only fail to promote collaboration among countries, it will exacerbate the ebb of globalisation.

Strengthening global economic cooperation requires several key elements: leadership, a platform for multilateral cooperation and domestic political support. From the 1990s until the global financial crisis, the United States was the leader in promoting global economic cooperation, through which the United States tried to promote the rules and institutions it supported; The platforms for Global Economic co-operation range from the traditional Bretton Woods institutions to the emerging G20 and a variety of specialised multilateral organisations; The domestic political forces driving global economic cooperation include the multinational corporations that have benefited most from globalization, while the general public has also benefited to some extent from the benefits of rapid economic growth and has a generally positive attitude towards globalization.

In the wake of the global financial crisis, the rise of trade protectionism, the intensification of geopolitical conflicts and the growing influence of populism have all impacted on the basis of global cooperation. After Donald Trump was elected president of the United States, the United States challenged the tradition of the international order several times, causing widespread controversy in the international community. The United States no longer has the capacity or the will to support multilateral cooperation. The legitimacy of the traditional Bretton Woods system has been undermined by the slow progress of reform, while the emerging G20 platform faces the embarrassing situation of being marginalized. Economic and social problems abound in western countries, and income inequality is becoming more and more serious, which leads to polarization and antagonism of domestic political power. In periods of steady economic growth, people are more optimistic and open minded, but in periods of relative economic downturn, they become more pessimistic and more closed off to outsiders. Radical globalisation no longer has a popular base.

Emerging infectious disease, among others, is a by product of globalisation. In the context of globalization, the increasing mobility of people and goods has also made the spread of disease faster and wider. In the absence of a better response, isolation is the only alternative to the epidemic. It is expected that countries will impose stricter controls on the cross-border movement of people and goods even if the outbreak disappears. In the face of the challenge of the epidemic, countries as a result of different responses, it is possible to blame each other, each other to prevent the situation. The spread of disease can easily be accompanied by "stigmatization" of specific populations, leading to more discrimination and exclusion. Under such circumstances, the new crown epidemic may become another shock to globalization in the wake of the global financial crisis, trade protectionism and geopolitical conflicts, and the speed of the ebb tide of globalization will be further accelerated, from a long historical perspective, this is the "beginning of the end" of a golden age of globalisation.

(the writer is a professor at the Shanghai Jiao Tong University, and chief economist at entropy capital. Zhu He, Xu Peiyu and Huang Wanjing work at entropy capital Global Macro Research Institute; Editor: Su Qi)
